Encapsulation is the OOP principle of:
Binding data (variables) and the methods that operate on that data into a single unit (class), while restricting direct access to the data and allowing controlled access through methods.

Java achieves encapsulation using two tools together:

Tool 1: Access Modifiers (MOST IMPORTANT) :
| Modifier    | Visibility             |
| ----------- | ---------------------- |
| `private`   | Only inside same class |
| `default`   | Same package           |
| `protected` | Package + subclass     |
| `public`    | Everywhere             |
Encapsulation = primarily private variables

Tool 2: Getter & Setter Methods
These methods: Expose data indirectly, Apply rules / validation, Control read/write permissions
Example:
class Account {
    private double balance; // hidden data

    // READ access
    public double getBalance() {
        return balance;
    }

    // WRITE access with validation
    public void deposit(double amount) {
        if (amount > 0) {
            balance += amount;
        }
    }

    public void withdraw(double amount) {
        if (amount > 0 && amount <= balance) {
            balance -= amount;
        }
    }
}

Usage:
Account acc = new Account();
acc.deposit(1000);
acc.withdraw(300);
System.out.println(acc.getBalance()); // 700
